tspan.tspan: Parent Method = St Simon's Bob Doubles
Divide the place notation (in column pn) of the parent method into places made below the hunt bell(s),
places made by the hunt bell(s), and places made above the hunt bell(s).
These places are entered in the columns headed B, H, and A respectively.
Rotate the method if needed so that (1) if the parent has an odd number of hunt bells,
the lower place of the middle hunt bell (or the only hunt bell) is the last change of the lead; or
(2) if the parent has an even number of hunt bells, the lower places of the middle two hunt
bells (or the only two hunt bells) are either side of the last change of the lead.
Increase the higher place of the hunt bell(s) by one place.
Add places for the additional hunt bell two changes after the places for the last hunt bell.
Note that this may involve wrapping back to the start of the lead.
Move the places below the hunt bells to be one change later in the lead.
Move the places above the hunt bells that are before the hunt bells reach their higher places up by one place.
Move the places above the hunt bells that are after the hunt bells reach their higher places up by one place and two changes later.
Rotate the resulting method if needed so that (1) if the extension has an odd number of hunt bells,
the lower place of the middle hunt bell is the last change of the lead; or
(2) if the extension has an even number of hunt bells, the lower place of the first of the middle two hunt
bells (or the first of the only two hunt bells) is the last change of the lead.
